Scipy¶

The scipy package contains various toolboxes dedicated to common issues in scientific computing. Its different submodules correspond to different applications, such as interpolation, integration, optimization, image processing, statistics, special functions, etc.

scipy can be compared to other standard scientific-computing libraries, such as the GSL (GNU Scientific Library for C and C++), or Matlabs toolboxes. scipy is the core package for scientific routines in Python; it is meant to operate efficiently on numpy arrays, so that numpy and scipy work hand in hand.

Before implementing a routine, it is worth checking if the desired data processing is not already implemented in Scipy. As non-professional programmers, scientists often tend to re-invent the wheel, which leads to buggy, non-optimal, difficult-to-share and unmaintainable code. By contrast, Scipys routines are optimized and tested, and should therefore be used when possible

A simple wave¶

In [7]:
freq = 1 #hz - cycles per second
amplitude = 1
sample_rate = 50 # samples per second
total_sample_time = 3 # second
num_samples = sample_rate * total_sample_time

t = np.linspace(0, total_sample_time, num_samples)
sig = [amplitude * np.sin(2*np.pi * freq * i) for i in t]

plt.figure(figsize=(14,7))
plt.plot(t, sig)
ax = plt.gca()
ax.set_title('Time Domain')
ax.set_xlabel('Time[s]')
ax.set_ylabel('Amplitude')
plt.show()

fft_output = fftpack.fft(sig)

magnitude = np.abs(fft_output)/fft_output.size
frequencies = fftpack.fftfreq(fft_output.size, d=1/sample_rate)

plt.figure(figsize=(14,7))
plt.plot(frequencies, magnitude)
plt.show()

Filter¶

In [16]:
def butter_design(cutoff, fs, order=5):
    nyq = 0.5 * fs
    normal_cutoff = cutoff/nyq
    b, a = signal.butter(order, normal_cutoff, btype='low', analog=False) 
    return b, a

def butter_filter(data, cutoff, fs, order=5):
    b, a = butter_design(cutoff, fs, order)
    y = signal.filtfilt(b, a, data)
    return y

# Filter requirements.
order = 5
fs = sample_rate_audio       # sample rate, Hz
cutoff = 500  # desired cutoff frequency of the filter, Hz

# Get the filter coefficients so we can check its frequency response.
b, a = butter_design(cutoff, fs, order)

# Plot the frequency response.
w, h = signal.freqz(b, a)

plt.figure(figsize=(14,7))
plt.subplot(2, 1, 1)
plt.plot(0.5*fs*w/np.pi, np.abs(h), 'b')
plt.plot(cutoff, 0.5*np.sqrt(2), 'ko')
plt.axvline(cutoff, color='k')
#plt.xlim(0, 0.5*fs)
plt.xlim(0, 1500)
plt.title("Lowpass Filter Frequency Response")
plt.xlabel('Frequency [Hz]')
plt.grid()


# Filter the data, and plot both the original and filtered signals.
y = butter_filter(input_audio, cutoff, fs, order)

plt.subplot(2, 1, 2)
plt.plot(time_array, input_audio, 'b-', label='data')
plt.plot(time_array, y, 'g-', linewidth=2, label='filtered data')
plt.xlabel('Time [sec]')
plt.grid()
plt.legend()

plt.subplots_adjust(hspace=0.35)
plt.show()
